{
  "doc_id": "10540",
  "text": "There have been no randomised trials of any form of surgery for refractory digital ulceration in patients with SSc-related digital ulcers [CITATION_1] . The aim of surgery is to prevent or minimise tissue damage, preserve hand function and improve quality of life. A number of different procedures have been advocated [CITATION_2] , but the one most commonly performed is probably surgical debridement of necrotic tissue, although this will vary between centres. In recent years, there has been increasing interest in digital (palmar) sympathectomy [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , a highly specialist procedure which should be considered in patients with severe digital ulcers and/or critical ischemia.",
